{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "kantian-expert",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Agree with Option B, one caveat on bridging",
    "content": "Agree with Option B. The terminological decisions are reference material — readers will return to them while reading specific essays, not absorb them linearly before starting. Moving them to a glossary introduction places them where they'll actually be used, and the Preface becomes a genuine narrative invitation rather than half-narrative, half-dictionary. \n\nOne caveat: the 形 reinterpretation section (which stays) already functions as a terminological entry. If it stays while the rest of the terminology moves, the Preface should briefly acknowledge the glossary's existence — something like a single sentence at the end of the 形 section: \"Further terminological decisions are explained in the introduction to the glossary.\" This prevents the reader from wondering why one term got special treatment in the Preface while others didn't — the answer is that 形 is a hermeneutical departure, not just a translation choice, and that distinction justifies its placement.\n\nAgree with both smaller trims as well."
  }
}
